<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The tibia of the leg I in male is strongly flattened dorsally (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 129–135" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 129 - 135. First leg of male 129 Pachyballus castaneus 130 Peplometus biscutellatus 131, 132 P. chlorophthalmus 133 P. congoensis 134 P. oyo 135 P. nimba 132 retrolateral view, others prolateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures129-135" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427075" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">131</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 154–159" captionStartId="F29" captionText="Figures 154 - 159. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, male 154 habitus, dorsal view 155 habitus, ventral view 156 habitus, lateral view 157 first leg, dorsal view 158 first leg, prolateral view 159 first leg, retrolateral view (specimen from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures154-159" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427080" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">158</figureCitation>
). The female is difficult to distinguish from 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. biscutellatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="biscutellatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. biscutellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it has a narrower abdomen (see Diagnosis of the latter species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="redescription">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Redescription.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Male.</emphasis>
Measurements. Cephalothorax: length 1.0-1.5, width 1.1-1.3, height 0.5-0.6. Eye field: length 0.6-0.8, anterior width 1.0-1.2, posterior width 1.2-1.3. Abdomen: length 2.2-2.3, width 1.4-1.5.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
General appearance as in Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 154–159" captionStartId="F29" captionText="Figures 154 - 159. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, male 154 habitus, dorsal view 155 habitus, ventral view 156 habitus, lateral view 157 first leg, dorsal view 158 first leg, prolateral view 159 first leg, retrolateral view (specimen from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures154-159" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427080" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">154-156</figureCitation>
. Small spider with flattened body. Carapace dark brown to blackish, pitted. White bristles around anterior median eyes and between all eyes of first row. Clypeus low, black, with a few white hairs. Fang of chelicerae short, two small teeth on promargin, retromarginal tooth with four tips (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 160–165" captionStartId="F30" captionText="Figures 160 - 165. Peplometus chlorophthalmus 160 cheliceral dentition 161, 163 palpal organ, ventral view 162, 164 palpal organ, lateral view 165 immature specimen (160 - 162 holotype 163, 164 specimen from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures160-165" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427081" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">160</figureCitation>
). Sternum oval, dark brown. Abdomen narrow, covered with strongly sclerotised, pitted, dark integument. Venter with typical scuta (same as by 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. biscutellatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="biscutellatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. biscutellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Legs yellowish with dark lines along femora and tibiae III and IV on prolateral surface. Legs I the stoutest, tip of prolateral side of femur with small patch, tibia strongly thickened, black with yellow line along dorsum and large light patch on retrolateral side, long flattened black setae ventrally (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 154–159" captionStartId="F29" captionText="Figures 154 - 159. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, male 154 habitus, dorsal view 155 habitus, ventral view 156 habitus, lateral view 157 first leg, dorsal view 158 first leg, prolateral view 159 first leg, retrolateral view (specimen from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures154-159" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427080" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">157</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 154–159" captionStartId="F29" captionText="Figures 154 - 159. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, male 154 habitus, dorsal view 155 habitus, ventral view 156 habitus, lateral view 157 first leg, dorsal view 158 first leg, prolateral view 159 first leg, retrolateral view (specimen from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures154-159" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427080" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">159</figureCitation>
). Tibia I characteristic for having a large flattened part on dorsal side (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 129–135" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 129 - 135. First leg of male 129 Pachyballus castaneus 130 Peplometus biscutellatus 131, 132 P. chlorophthalmus 133 P. congoensis 134 P. oyo 135 P. nimba 132 retrolateral view, others prolateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures129-135" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427075" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">131</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 154–159" captionStartId="F29" captionText="Figures 154 - 159. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, male 154 habitus, dorsal view 155 habitus, ventral view 156 habitus, lateral view 157 first leg, dorsal view 158 first leg, prolateral view 159 first leg, retrolateral view (specimen from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures154-159" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427080" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">158</figureCitation>
). Pedipalp light, its structure as in Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 160–165" captionStartId="F30" captionText="Figures 160 - 165. Peplometus chlorophthalmus 160 cheliceral dentition 161, 163 palpal organ, ventral view 162, 164 palpal organ, lateral view 165 immature specimen (160 - 162 holotype 163, 164 specimen from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures160-165" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427081" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">161-164</figureCitation>
, embolic coil wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Female.</emphasis>
Measurements. Cephalothorax: length 1.0-1.4, width 1.1-1.3, height 0.5-0.6. Eye field: length 0.6-0.7, anterior width 1.0-1.2, posterior width 1.2-1.3. Abdomen: length 2.0-2.4, width 1.5-1.8.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures160-165" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427081" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" start="Figures 160–165" startId="F30">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Figures 160-165.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Peplometus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peplometus chlorophthalmus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chlorophthalmus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Peplometus chlorophthalmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">160</emphasis>
cheliceral dentition 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">161, 163</emphasis>
palpal organ, ventral view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">162, 164</emphasis>
palpal organ, lateral view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">165</emphasis>
immature specimen (
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">160-162</emphasis>
holotype 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">163, 164</emphasis>
specimen from Congo).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
Similar to male, general appearance as in Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 166–171" captionStartId="F31" captionText="Figures 166 - 171. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, female 166 habitus, dorsal view 167 habitus, ventral view 168, 169 epigyne 170 internal structure of epigyne, ventral view 171 internal structure of epigyne, dorsal view (171 specimen from Natal, other specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures166-171" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427083" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">166</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 166–171" captionStartId="F31" captionText="Figures 166 - 171. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, female 166 habitus, dorsal view 167 habitus, ventral view 168, 169 epigyne 170 internal structure of epigyne, ventral view 171 internal structure of epigyne, dorsal view (171 specimen from Natal, other specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures166-171" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427083" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">167</figureCitation>
. White hairs at anterior eyes and on posterior carapace slope. Abdomen wider than in male, but relatively narrow, narrower than in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. biscutellatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="biscutellatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. biscutellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Legs darker than in male. Femora of I-III legs brown with yellow ventral surface, femora IV completely brown. Patellae IV with pro- and retrolateral brown stripes. First leg not larger, its tibia black with black long setae ventrally, in some specimens with narrow light streak along dorsum. Tibiae II with prolateral brown stripe, tibiae IV brown with thin yellow longitudinal stripes dorsally and ventrally. Other leg segments light yellow. Palps blackish. Epigyne as in Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 166–171" captionStartId="F31" captionText="Figures 166 - 171. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, female 166 habitus, dorsal view 167 habitus, ventral view 168, 169 epigyne 170 internal structure of epigyne, ventral view 171 internal structure of epigyne, dorsal view (171 specimen from Natal, other specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures166-171" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427083" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">168</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 166–171" captionStartId="F31" captionText="Figures 166 - 171. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, female 166 habitus, dorsal view 167 habitus, ventral view 168, 169 epigyne 170 internal structure of epigyne, ventral view 171 internal structure of epigyne, dorsal view (171 specimen from Natal, other specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures166-171" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427083" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">169</figureCitation>
, rectangular with shallow depression. Ventral structure of epigyne similar to other species, copulatory ducts long, weakly sclerotised in initial part, forming several loops (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 166–171" captionStartId="F31" captionText="Figures 166 - 171. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, female 166 habitus, dorsal view 167 habitus, ventral view 168, 169 epigyne 170 internal structure of epigyne, ventral view 171 internal structure of epigyne, dorsal view (171 specimen from Natal, other specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures166-171" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427083" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">170</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 166–171" captionStartId="F31" captionText="Figures 166 - 171. Peplometus chlorophthalmus, female 166 habitus, dorsal view 167 habitus, ventral view 168, 169 epigyne 170 internal structure of epigyne, ventral view 171 internal structure of epigyne, dorsal view (171 specimen from Natal, other specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures166-171" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427083" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">171</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Immature specimens.</emphasis>
Abdomen not elongated, heart-shaped, with two oval scuta on dorsum, close to each other, not covering whole dorsum of abdomen (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 160–165" captionStartId="F30" captionText="Figures 160 - 165. Peplometus chlorophthalmus 160 cheliceral dentition 161, 163 palpal organ, ventral view 162, 164 palpal organ, lateral view 165 immature specimen (160 - 162 holotype 163, 164 specimen from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures160-165" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427081" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">165</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The first description of the female is given here. Simon described only the male of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. chlorophthalmus" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="chlorophthalmus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. chlorophthalmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although the vial with a type specimen contains also an undescribed female and a few immature specimens. This material is however in a very poor condition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
Length of the apical part of embolus varies. It is very long in South African specimen, extending beyond the retrolateral edge of apical part of cymbium (Figs 
